        text: "Felicia Day calls your inner self your Hero Self. It is the part of you that needs to be reconnected with and grown. This is where your real creativity lives.\n\nAt the core of all of this is a deep pull to show your authentic self. You want others to see your strengths, your flaws, and your strange edges. You want to be accepted as you are.\n\nStill, you have to ask yourself some real questions. Who am I, and what do I have to offer the world? Do you actually know the answer?\n\nIt helps to spend time with the real you. We tend to copy what the people around us do. It is easier. But does that make life meaningful? Not really.\n\nMaybe you feel like you are just drifting through the days. You are not really living. By getting to know yourself and shaping your Hero Self, you start to live honestly. You start to feel present.\n\nTry spending an hour with yourself. What do you like? What do you dislike? What matters to you, and why? What are your dreams for the years ahead?\n\nKids are curious and creative by nature. They have not yet learned to push that side down. They find joy in almost everything. They do not ask why something should make sense. They just enjoy it.\n\nAs adults, we expect everything to make sense. If it does not, we ignore it. Felicia Day shares that her child makes up games that seem to make no sense. Yet the joy in those games is catching. That is the energy you need to find again. A child lives with open wonder. So can you."
