        text: "To reach your creative side, you need to let your emotions move. Feelings sit at the center of creativity, and you cannot fully tap it while holding everything in. The more you talk about and share what you feel, the more your imagination opens up.\n\nMany of us keep feelings locked away. Society has a way of making us believe that expressing emotion is a sign of weakness. The opposite is closer to the truth.\n\nSit down and think about the things that make you happy. Think about what brings you sadness. Then ask what makes you angry. Look for the patterns and the triggers. The better you understand your own feelings, the freer they become. You can also learn to use their energy.\n\nDaydreams can help you tap your creativity. When you are watching TV and a beautiful house appears, do you picture living there? That kind of wondering strengthens your creative thinking.\n\nLetting your mind drift is good for creativity. Start daydreaming on purpose.\n\nEveryone has dreams. By definition, dreams are not likely to come true. That does not mean you cannot try. To bring a dream into reality, picture it clearly and make a plan of action. As Felicia Day says, dream it, question it, then commit to it."
