        text: "As adults, we tend to block our own creativity because what comes out of our minds does not always make sense. But who says it has to make sense in the moment? Creativity is about making dreams come true and trying new ideas. If an idea sounds strange today, that is fine. It may make sense tomorrow.\n\nThe point of being creative is the willingness to try and fail. You will not know what works until you play with ideas, test them, fail a little, and try again. Some of the best ideas in the world came from that kind of process. You will not know your own potential unless you try.\n\nChildren think creatively and playfully. They do not stop to ask whether something makes sense. You have seen that joy on their faces when they play and imagine. You can have that too if you let your mind open and your creativity move without waiting for approval. As that happens, you will feel a real lift in your happiness.\n\nWe are surrounded by social media, technology, and countless distractions. It is easy to block our creativity without even noticing. Becoming aware of the reasons can help you tap into your natural creative side and put it to work for you.\n\nA simple way to start is to recapture the fun of your childhood by revisiting the things you used to enjoy. Try learning to draw or doodle, simply being creative with a pen and paper, and see what your mind comes up with when it is not questioning everything. Walk through your home and declutter any space that makes you feel stuck or small."
